Chinese Stocks in the U.S.: China Mobile, China Telecom, Suntech

-- B y   B e l i n d a   C a o
-- 
2011-09-14T21:11:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-14/chinese-stocks-in-the-u-s-china-mobile-china-telecom-suntech.html
The Bank of New York Mellon China
ADR Index, which tracks American depositary receipts, gained 1.5
percent to 390.57. The New York Stock Exchange China Index
climbed 1.3 percent to 238.92. The Shanghai Composite Index
added 0.5 percent to 2,484.83.  The following companies were among the most active Chinese
shares in New York trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses and
prices are as of the close of trading at 4 p.m. New York time.  China Mobile Ltd. (941)  , the world’s biggest phone
carrier by subscribers, climbed 2.7 percent to $51.62, the
highest in 10 months. The company will partner with the U.S.-
based broadband provider Clearwire Corp. on the TD-LTE
technology for mobile devices and on worldwide data roaming,
according to a statement of China Mobile through Globe Newswire.  China Unicom ( Hong Kong ) Ltd. (CHU US), the nation’s
second-largest mobile-phone carrier, advanced 2.5 percent to a
three-month high of $21.97. The company said its unit China
United Network Communications Ltd. will sell 8 billion yuan
($1.25 billion) of commercial paper on Sept. 15 in two tranches,
according to its statement to the Hong Kong Stock Exchange.  China Telecom Corp. (CHA US), the nation’s biggest fixed-
line phone carrier, increased 2.4 percent, the most in three
weeks, to $65.42. The company plans to introduce Apple Inc.’s
iPhone 5 in October, according to CapitalVue.com, citing a
report in Southern Metropolis Daily.  Silvercorp Metals Inc. (SVM)  , a Vancouver-based Chinese
silver mine owner which was accused of fraud in an anonymous
letter last month, rose for the first day in four, gaining 2.9
percent to $6.48. The company rejected another report published
yesterday that questioned the quality of its ore and volume of
sales to a related party, according to a statement distributed
through Marketwire.  Suntech Power Holdings (STP US), the world’s largest maker
of solar panels, dropped 6.1 percent to a record low of $3.85.
The average price of polysilicon, the raw material for solar
modules, fell 1.3 percent from the previous week to $49.38 a
kilogram on lower demand, according to EnergyTrend. Solar
modules have declined 1.3 percent to $1.12 a watt since last
week, EnergyTrend said today in an e-mailed statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
